%T A395671 26624,28160,35625,37179,39424,47500,50688,71250,71875,74358,79872,
%U A395671 83125,84480,95000,106875,118272,120960,130625,133120,140800,142500,143750,148716,152064,154375,166250
%N A395671 Let S(n,b) be the number of trailing zeros in base b. Sequence gives b = Product (p_i)^(e_i) such that S(n,b) < min{S(n,(p_i)^(e_i)) : e_i*(p_i-1) maximum}. See comments.
%C A395671 Let b = Product (p_i)^(e_i) be the canonical factorization of b. Then for all sufficiently large n, S(n,b) is determined by S(n,(p_i)^(e_i)) with maximum e_i*(p_i-1). For most b this is even true for all n. Sequence gives b such that exceptional n values exist.
%C A395671 In other words, b = Product (p_i)^(e_i) is a term if and only if there exists n such that S(n,(p_i0)^(e_i0)) < min{S(n,(p_i)^(e_i)) : e_i*(p_i-1) maximum} for some i0. A more detailed introduction of the background is in the Math Stack Exchange link below.
%C A395671 It is possible for a term to have maximum (p_i)^(e_i) reached multiple times:
%C A395671  - For b = 2^27 * 3^14 * 5^7, we have 27*(2-1) < 14*(3-1) = 7*(5-1), and S(30,2^27) = 0 < S(30,3^14) = S(30,5^7) = 1.
%C A395671  - For b = 3^23 * 5^12 * 7^8, we have 23*(3-1) < 12*(5-1) = 8*(7-1), and S(50,3^23) = 0 < S(50,5^12) = S(50,7^8) = 1.
%C A395671  - For b = 2^51 * 3^26 * 5^13, we have 51*(2-1) < 26*(3-1) = 13*(5-1), and S(55,2^51) = 0 < S(55,3^26) = S(55,5^13) = 1.
%C A395671  - For b = 2^58 * 3^30 * 7^10, we have 58*(2-1) < 30*(3-1) = 10*(7-1), and S(63,2^58) = 0 < S(63,3^30) = S(63,7^10) = 1. The same applies to b = 2^59 * 3^30 * 7^10.
%C A395671  - For b = 3^77 * 5^39 * 7^26, we have 77*(3-1) < 39*(5-1) = 26*(7-1), and S(161,3^77) = 0 < S(161,5^39) = S(161,7^26) = 1.
%H A395671 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395671/b395671.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..832</a>
%H A395671 Math Stack Exchange, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/5136175/in-base-b-p-1e-1p-2e-2-with-e-1p-1-1e-2p-2-1-the-of-trailing-z">In base b=p1^e1*p2^e2 with e1*(p1-1)<e2*(p2-1), the # of trailing zeros of n! is determined by p2; what about the exceptional n?</a>.
%H A395671 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395671/a395671_2.txt">List of exceptional values n in each base b</a>.
%H A395671 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395671/a395671_1.txt">PARI Program</a>.
%e A395671 Let n = 224 = 2^5 * 7^1. Since 5*(2-1) < 1*(7-1), we have S(n,224) = S(n,7^1) for all n, with only one exceptional value n = 7, where S(n,2^5) = 0 and S(n,7^1) = 1.
%e A395671 Let n = 3456 = 3^3 * 2^7. Since 3*(3-1) < 7*(2-1), we have S(n,3456) = S(n,2^7) for all n, with only one exceptional value n = 8, where S(n,3^3) = 0 and S(n,2^7) = 1.
%o A395671 (PARI) \\ See link. Note that the code requires PARI/GP version 2.14 or higher.
